observations.recommendation:
Management re-evaluates or re-computes the amounts of honoraria received by the BAC members, secretariat and TWG using the maximum rates for each completed projects conducted through public bidding and other modes of procurement as allowed pursuant to DBM Budget Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3.  If found out that the honoraria received was higher than the allowed amount, require the concerned personnel to refund the excess amount.

Refund the amount of ₱7,000.00, as this is not a valid fund source for the payment of honorarium in January 2021;

Strictly observe the guidelines on the grant of honorarium to the LGU’s personnel involved in government procurement in accordance with the provisions set forth in DBM Budget Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3.

The City Mayor together with the participants secure and submit the following:

·   Authorization from the DILG for the conduct of the capability-building seminar;
·   Sangguniang Panlungsod resolution for the use of funds;
·   Program of Activity for the entire capability-building seminar;
·   Narrative report of each participant; and
·        Other lacking documents as mentioned.

The amount of ₱13,500.00 for excessive accommodation be paid by each participant.

Before conducting a Capability-Building Seminar, and the like, secure all the necessary documents pursuant to the DILG-DBM JMC No. 2 and that liquidations are properly supported with correct documentation and that expenses are valid and not excessive.

We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the:
CTO to provide a copy of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year to the CAO at the beginning of the year;
CAO to prepare the journal entries to record the debit to RPT/SET Receivables and credit to Deferred RPT/SET Income based on the certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year submitted by the CTO at the beginning of the year;
CAO to analyze and reconcile records to trace back the difference between the RPT/SET Receivables and the corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts and prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to record the reconciling items to present the correct balances of the accounts in the FS; and
City Accountant or the assigned personnel to recognize prior years’ tax collections as adjustments to government equity, instead of recording them as part of the current year income, to correctly present the amounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed:
Through the City Veterinarian and Accountant, to retrieve relevant records and documents on the breeding stocks acquired in CY 2022 and the previous years;
Through the City Agriculturist/Veterinarian, to conduct year-end physical inventory count of the biological assets with its corresponding fair value less cost to sell measurement duly determined by the City Agriculturist pursuant to Section 4.5 of COA Circular No. 2016-004 and submit the report as well as the monthly report on the death, dispersal or transfer of ownership of animals, addition/new born with estimated fair value less cost to sell of these animals as determined by the City Agriculturist to the City Accountant;
Through the City Accountant, to prepare and regularly update the WOABSLC and book up the necessary adjustments for the transfers of ownership, distributions, deaths and changes in fair market value of the Biological Assets account and thereafter, prudently apply all the accounting rules and regulations prescribed under IPSAS 27 pertaining to these assets;
In coordination with the concerned offices, to craft or formulate specific guidelines or a clearly defined policy on its animal dispersal program; and
To direct the CVO to revisit the MOA and ensure that the conditions, terms, roles and responsibilities of the parties in the future are clearly embodied therein.

We recommended and Management agreed:
To instruct the OIC-City Accountant to send demand letters, requiring the concerned personnel to immediately settle their overdue cash advances in full;
Through the OIC-City Accountant, to initiate the necessary procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2023-008 for the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances that have been dormant;
To enjoin the Accountable Officers to observe the prescribed period of liquidating cash advances and ensure full liquidation at year-end through the submission of liquidation reports along with the requisite supporting documents, or by refunding any remaining balances in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002;
To direct the OIC-City Accountant to ensure regular monitoring of cash advance liquidations to prevent any delays in their accounting and recording;
To direct the OIC-City Accountant to record the liquidation of cash advances on the date the Reports of Disbursements or Liquidation Reports, as the case may be, together with the supporting documents, were submitted to the CAO;
To designate additional Disbursing Officers or increase the fidelity bond premium of the existing accountable officers; and
To ensure that all Accountable Officers are properly bonded.

We recommended that Management re-evaluate or re-compute the amounts of honoraria received by the BAC members, secretariat and TWG using the maximum rates for each completed projects conducted through public bidding and other modes of procurement as allowed pursuant to DBM Budget Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3.  If found out that the honoraria received was higher than the allowed amount, require the concerned personnel to refund the excess amount.

Refund the amount of ₱7,000.00, as this is not a valid fund source for the payment of honorarium in January 2021;

Strictly observe the guidelines on the grant of honorarium to the LGU’s personnel involved in government procurement in accordance with the provisions set forth in DBM Budget Circular Nos. 2004-5A and 2007-3.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

The City Mayor together with the participants secure and submit the following:

Authorization from the DILG for the conduct of the capability-building seminar;
Sangguniang Panlungsod resolution for the use of funds;
Program of Activity for the entire capability-building seminar;
Narrative report of each participant; and
Other lacking documents as mentioned herein.

The amount of ₱13,500.00 for excessive accommodation be paid by each participant.

Before conducting a Capability-Building Seminar, and the like, secure all the necessary documents pursuant to the DILG-DBM JMC No. 2 and that liquidations are properly supported with correct documentation and that expenses are valid and not excessive.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the City Accountant to trace the transactions in the SLs of the account Cash Local Treasury of the previous accounting system and effect the necessary recording or adjustments in the current SL of the e-NGAS to properly reflect the transactions of each fund;
Require the City Accountant to review and analyze the entries in the SL to determine what had caused the abnormal balances of the Cash Local Treasury especially in SEF and TF books and take the necessary actions in order to correct them;
Instruct the City Treasurer to update the cash book balances to facilitate monitoring of undeposited balances; and
Instruct the City Accountant to coordinate with the City Treasurer to reconcile the balances per books and cash books.

We recommended that Management direct the City Accountant to:
Submit the subsidiary ledgers/schedules showing the composition of the assets recorded under the PPE accounts as presented in the Statement of Financial Position;
Review and submit a revised depreciation schedule following the guidelines provided in IPSAS 17, taking into account the above noted deficiencies;
Prepare the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts in order to present fairly the financial statements.
This observation was relayed to Management through AOM No. 2022-024 (2021) dated February 28, 2022.

The Local Chief Executive to:
Ensure compliance with the provisions pertaining to the receipts and distributions of the donations in-kind received by the City so that they will be properly accounted for;
Direct the City Social Welfare and Development Officer to prepare and submit the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances within ten working days after the end of each quarter as prescribed in the circular.

The Management to:

support other barangays with no MRF in terms of financial and technical aspect of implementing the Materials Recovery Facility (MRF);
provide a functional Eco-Enforcers as provided in the plan to help the City Solid Waste Management Ordinance and other environmental ordinance especially during the collection activity of the Private Collector;

organize an effective information drive campaign about the importance of garbage segregation in different areas of the City to apprise the people of the strict implementation of the Mandatory Segregation of Solid Wastes policy, and

implement the existing penalties for violations of as provided under RA 9003, City Ordinances and other pertinent rules and regulations.

Management to:

Comply strictly with the provisions of Section 89 of PD 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

Require the City Accountant to request for the write-off of cash advances in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 and to make necessary adjusting journal entry/entries to unliquidated cash advances due to erroneous posting.

