The City Accountant to: 

To not include appropriations for capital outlays in the transfer of unutilized appropriation from the General Fund to the Trust Liability – DRRMF under the Trust Fund books until the projects funded therefore are completed pursuant to above mentioned COA Circulars;

Verify the appropriations for capital outlay not yet implemented but included in the Trust Liability – DRRMF balance and make the necessary adjusting entry to transfer it back to the general fund appropriations until project has been completed;

To include in the monthly Reports on Utilization of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund the continuing appropriation for capital outlay projects, for transparency purposes.

Require that:

The City Treasurer, as acting GSO of the City, number each type of supplies and maintain Stock Cards per stock number;

Require each end-user Offices the preparation of Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) for supplies used during the period and submit the same to the City Treasurer;

The City Treasurer, based on the submitted RIS by the different Offices, consolidate the issuance of inventories through the preparation of Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit the same to the City Accountant on a weekly basis;

The City Accountant maintain the Supplies Ledger Card and to record the receipt and issuances of supplies and also to provide computation of the inventory based on a weighted average method. Likewise, prepare the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers to record related inventory expenses based on the submitted SSMI; and

To require the conduct of physical count of inventories on semi-annual and annual basis and prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Auditor following the deadline discussed above.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Ensure compliance with the provisions pertaining to the receipts and distributions of the donations in-kind received by the City so that they will be properly accounted for;
Direct the City Social Welfare and Development Officer to prepare and submit the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances within ten working days after the end of each quarter as prescribed in the circular.

Management should require the City Accountant to:

submit the depreciation schedules of the property, plant and equipment accounts for the proper computation of amounts necessary in the adjustments;

observe consistency in recording of the transactions to prevent inaccurate and misleading information pursuant to Section 111 of PD 1445.

Establish a criteria/standard that will serve basis on how the performance of the contractor will be measured. In addition to the right to cancel the contract, it should also include penalties for minor deviations, Specifically, the City may consider, among others, the reduction of the amount payable to the contractor equivalent to the cost of services that have not been delivered;

Impose penalties for reported violation of the terms and conditions under the contract and set a fixed amount of penalty based on the violation and/or omissions committed by the contractor; and

Create a monitoring team and develop strategies to facilitate assessment of efficiency of performance of the contractors.

